Question by  

Would you offer a fully diluted SAFT instead of a net exercise price from equity to a portfolio company? If so, What's a 'fair' %?

Question by  

Would you offer a fully diluted SAFT instead of a net exercise price from equity to a portfolio company? If so, What's a 'fair' %?

There are two components to this question:

1) Would I offer a funding round as a SAFT / 'token only' without equity to a project?

2) Would and when would I structure a funding round with a fixed token network valuation?

1) The short answer is: No.

While this used to be the meta within crypto venture, there have been too many instances where a token network launch failed to find traction and the company pivoted towards accruing value towards the equity company instead.

Getting exposure to both token and equity is a must have downside protection as an investor nowadays. 

A benefit to a founder in this case is that your investors are aligned with you whether you are building a token network or end up building an equity company.

This can matter quite a bit when it's still early and you're not sure which direction you'll be headed. There have been cases where founders have split investor groups up into two diverging interest groups: one side with more token network ownership and another with more equity exposure.

This results in diverging investor groups pushing for two seperate project outcomes. This can still happen without diverging interest groups and with investors with different visions for the company. A situation you want to avoid at all costs for obvious reasons.

There are other reasons such as: there being both value accrual to the core company after the launch of a token network (eg. Saas business models)... And it's also common for the core company to continue operating and building new products - using the funding secured by an original set of investors, etc.
As such, meta nowadays is for an investor to invest in both the token network and company.

2) Would and when would I structure a funding round with a fixed token network valuation?

Short answer: Only in later stage rounds.

Years ago, a 'fixed fdnv SAFT' was standard practice, but over the last few years, we've realized that this was harmful for early stage teams in particular situations.

This was because it limited the amount of capital a team could raise in the future as they couldn't continuously dilute by raising more as they'd sold permanent portions of their future token network.  

This can be okay at late stages when you can plan out your network ownership composition at launch.

But in early stages, when you're so far away from launching a network - you simply need the optionality.

However, this doesn't apply if you know that you're immediately launching a network or already a live network.

If you're thinking a bit more along the lines along "how much equity or token network ownership should I sell?"

There's no standard answer but generally, don't sell more than 20% equity in one round (dilution optionality) and ensure no investor owns more than 5-6% of the token network (governance concentration risk).

Early stage: 

Raise as SAFE with pro-rata token rights (for speed and flexibility on future token network composition). 

If I were purely focused on product and general execution initially, I'd focus on bringing on a single lead (70%+ of round) + 1-2 checks from small valuation sensitive funds.

Unless I were focused on wide distribution from day 1, I'd avoid too many angels in the earliest rounds. Typically, I've found angels aren't super valuation sensitive but are often the first to take money off the table and can hurt early markets far more than most legitimate lead funds. I'd bring them on later.

Angels can be incredibly helpful, but the majority aren't in reality. They're great cheerleaders when things are going well, but when things are not going well, it will be the partner at the lead fund who will be there in the trenches with you. Experiences here will obvs vary a lot but just my personal pref.

At later stages, I'd raise as a priced round (and in turn convert all outstanding SAFEs). This way I'm able to take on shared dilution across the cap table (SAFEs have fully rachet - meaning it that its promised future equity and can't yet be diluted just yet).

If I raised $9m with a SAFE at $90m val cap and sell the company at $10m, only $1m will be distributed to the rest of the founders (assuming founders owned 90% of the equity) as there was no 'bottom' valuation for the conversion of the convertible notes vs...

...if I raised $9m via priced round at $90m post (10% equity), then if I sell the company at $10m, all shareholders are treated equally (I'd get $9m if I owned 90% of the company). Trade off being investors have many more protective rights of course, but think it's a fair one.
Some quick thoughts!
Need to start an entity and structure it accordingly. And it really depends on how much actual community governance you'll want baked into the entity.

Light weight version can just be a membership club with light suggestive governance benefits. 

Heavy weight can include actual member voting from their equity representation.
To do this today, you'll need to work with a lawyer who's a DAO nerd with a corporate structuring background -> hit up  for intros ;)
Cost wise, it's not worth over structuring anything unless you're looking to raise at least 1-3m over a lifetime due to operational costs of membership KYC, tax admin, legal setup and more.

These are known as ‚Äòparty rounds‚Äô and I generally advise founders to avoid them as it doesn‚Äôt give any single investor any meaningful ownership to actually step in to help when needed. 

The exception is when it‚Äôs a party round full of strategic investors (often customers or communities) or angels.

To me this signals that no legitimate lead was willing to step in to lead the funding round (okay for pre-seed rounds but horrible later on at seed or later) but also at the same time that there‚Äôs going to be a ton of dead weight on the cap table.
This is not always the case but party round investors usually are of lower quality and often take money off the table far earlier as well (less pressure and reputation at risk).

Easiest way to generate investor interest is to build a product that people talk about and use. 

Next best is to be incredibly visible with a public presence pre-launch (good marketing, narrative design, brand building). 

Focus on doing either well and investors will either out naturally. It‚Äôs their job to do so.

https://warpcast.com/pet3rpan/0x7143eb28

Entirely depends. I usually run some math on their burn rate / capital expenditure relative to the outcomes achieved. I'm okay for example with a team that have achieved a lot with marketshare / adoption but still with work to do on revenue - as opposed to having spent money and lots of time without much ground made.

During bull markets, you invest for the bear (lean towards fundamental teams that not only survive but become a dominant market leader) and during bear markets, you invest for the bull (lean towards teams that are highly capable of executing on something really big).

My biggest learnings as an investor were made during the shifts from: 

bear -> bull
bull -> bear
bear -> bull

Plenty of learnings on how to optimize in the future. Iterated game.

You'll basically never get it right. Too aggressive during the bull market and too passive during the bear market. You'll always been too late or too early.

 Goal is to get better over the long term.

I'd rather back a new team from scratch with better timing than a team with several rounds of dilution and lukewarm results. New teams have higher energy on average / less burned out, move faster, less org/eng debt and can raise a lot more capital without constraints.
Plenty of countering points of course. And I've made plenty of decisions on both sides.

One of the biggest things people don‚Äôt talk about is how most of your most favourite name dropped crypto products out there are mostly inhabited by bots. It‚Äôs a stark reality when you start to use and participate vs. cheer lead about it on the TL ‚úåÔ∏è
If this is the case, at least convert these bots into meaningful ARPU!

Social media gives you a warped view of the world. It allocates social capital to the digital local maxima giving you a sense that you need to emulate in order to be successful. In reality true 1% of the 1% operators succeed with it without social back patting, you just don‚Äôt meet them around much by chance.

It‚Äôs a shame majority of people are never exposed to such people, setting such a low bar for brilliance, work ethic, discipline and intellectual rigour. Meeting such people forces a harsh reality on you - sacrifice what you find comfort in or be eternally mediocre.

My point is not ‚Äúhustle porn blah be great, social media bad‚Äù but rather that the ideals of today are so low by default because of the new inherent social hierarchy in place.

And to not convince yourself of this mirage.
This is also not to diss the skill of influencing online - it‚Äôs an incredible skill that takes incredible discipline. I‚Äôve played the game and still do with varying levels of participation.

I‚Äôm just saying the truly great minds out there have far less social media than me. Even for myself, at some point I realized my self limits and decided to optimise vs. pushing at the edges. To invent, to break, to defy limits. Those people are not going to have the stereotypical profile of your average influencer.

I just sort of wonder how many people are completely dismissed and overlooked by the world because of their social status online. Or even the lack of ability for the crowd to perceive such individuals of true genius.
I'm not actually against or pro anything. I just love surfacing observations that I think no one is talking about openly for whatever reason ;)
